      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- SECTION 1: ADPIE -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section id="adpie" style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">
          1. ADPIE – Every Step Reviewed
        </h2>

        <!-- Assessment -->
        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Assessment</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Assessment is the <strong>first and continuous</strong> step of the nursing process. The nurse
          systematically collects, organises, validates, and documents data about a patient's health status.
          Without complete and accurate assessment, every subsequent step of the nursing process is compromised.
        </p>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Types of data collected:</strong></p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Subjective data</strong> – what the patient tells you (symptoms, feelings, perceptions). Example: "I feel nauseated and my head is pounding." Only the patient can report subjective data; it is recorded in quotation marks.</li>
          <li><strong>Objective data</strong> – measurable, observable findings collected through physical examination and diagnostic tests. Example: BP 168/94 mmHg, HR 102 bpm, skin flushed and diaphoretic.</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Types of assessment:</strong></p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Initial (admission) assessment</strong> – comprehensive head-to-toe database collected on first contact; establishes baseline.</li>
          <li><strong>Focused assessment</strong> – targeted assessment of a specific problem or body system (e.g., respiratory assessment for a patient with dyspnoea).</li>
          <li><strong>Emergency assessment</strong> – rapid, life-threatening situation (ABC: Airway, Breathing, Circulation first).</li>
          <li><strong>Time-lapsed reassessment</strong> – compares current status against earlier baseline; done at each shift or follow-up visit.</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Data sources include the patient (primary source), family/caregivers, the medical record, other
          healthcare team members, and laboratory/diagnostic results. The nurse validates data to ensure
          accuracy—for example, re-measuring an unexpected vital sign or asking a clarifying follow-up question.
        </p>

        <!-- Callout box -->
        <div style="background:#eff6ff; border-left:4px solid #bfdbfe; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem 1.25rem; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; font-weight:700; color:#1d4ed8; margin-bottom:0.4rem;">📋 Clinical Example – Assessment</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; color:#1e3a5f; line-height:1.7; margin:0;">
            Mrs. T., 72 years old, is admitted with confusion. The nurse collects subjective data by asking
            her family (surrogate source): <em>"She wasn't making sense this morning and didn't recognise me."</em>
            Objective data includes: GCS 12/15, T 38.9 °C, urine dark amber, specific gravity 1.030,
            HR 112 bpm. Both data types together guide the diagnosis of acute confusion related to dehydration
            and possible infection.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Diagnosis -->
        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Diagnosis</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          The nursing diagnosis is the nurse's clinical judgment about a patient's response to actual or
          potential health problems. It differs from a medical diagnosis (which identifies disease) in that
          it describes the <strong>human response</strong> to that disease or condition, which is within the
          nurse's scope of practice to treat.
        </p>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
          Nursing diagnoses are drawn from the <strong>NANDA-I</strong> (North American Nursing Diagnosis
          Association International) taxonomy. There are three main types:
        </p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Actual nursing diagnosis</strong> – problem that currently exists. Supported by defining characteristics (signs and symptoms).</li>
          <li><strong>Risk nursing diagnosis</strong> – potential problem that does not yet exist but for which the patient is vulnerable. Written as "Risk for…" with no defining characteristics required.</li>
          <li><strong>Health-promotion (wellness) diagnosis</strong> – readiness to move to a higher level of health. Written as "Readiness for Enhanced…"</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>PES format</strong> (for actual diagnoses):</p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>P</strong> – Problem (NANDA-I label): e.g., <em>Acute Pain</em></li>
          <li><strong>E</strong> – Etiology (related to / "r/t"): e.g., <em>related to surgical incision</em></li>
          <li><strong>S</strong> – Signs and Symptoms (as evidenced by / "aeb"): e.g., <em>as evidenced by patient rating pain 7/10, guarding abdomen, diaphoresis</em></li>
        </ul>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Full statement: <em>"Acute Pain related to surgical incision as evidenced by patient rating pain 7/10,
          guarding abdomen, and diaphoresis."</em> For risk diagnoses, there is no "S" (no current signs):
          <em>"Risk for Falls related to postoperative sedation and orthostatic hypotension."</em>
        </p>

        <!-- Planning -->
        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Planning</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          During planning, the nurse sets <strong>measurable, patient-centred goals</strong> and selects
          nursing interventions to achieve those goals. Planning produces the individualised care plan.
          Goals are written for the patient (what the patient will do), not the nurse.
        </p>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>SMART goals:</strong></p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>S</strong> – Specific: Who will do what?</li>
          <li><strong>M</strong> – Measurable: Observable, with a criterion (e.g., pain ≤ 3/10)</li>
          <li><strong>A</strong> – Attainable: Realistic given patient's condition and resources</li>
          <li><strong>R</strong> – Relevant: Directly addresses the nursing diagnosis</li>
          <li><strong>T</strong> – Time-bound: Specifies when the goal will be met (e.g., "within 30 minutes of analgesia administration")</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:0.75rem;">
          Example SMART goal: <em>"The patient will report pain ≤ 3/10 within 30 minutes of analgesic
          administration, as verbally stated to the nurse, by end of shift."</em>
        </p>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Prioritisation using Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs:</strong></p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Level 1 – Physiological needs</strong> (highest priority): airway, breathing, circulation, nutrition, fluid, elimination, rest. Always address life-threatening physiological problems first.</li>
          <li><strong>Level 2 – Safety and security</strong>: fall prevention, infection control, safe environment.</li>
          <li><strong>Level 3 – Love and belonging</strong>: social support, therapeutic relationship.</li>
          <li><strong>Level 4 – Esteem</strong>: self-confidence, dignity, autonomy.</li>
          <li><strong>Level 5 – Self-actualisation</strong> (lowest priority): personal growth, creativity.</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Additional prioritisation frameworks include the <strong>ABC</strong> method (Airway before
          Breathing before Circulation) and Maslow's hierarchy. Actual problems generally take priority
          over risk problems, and acute problems take priority over chronic ones.
        </p>

        <!-- Implementation -->
        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Implementation</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Implementation is the action phase—carrying out the planned interventions. The nurse must
          reassess the patient before each intervention to confirm it is still appropriate, and document
          all actions taken immediately after completion.
        </p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Independent interventions</strong>: Actions the nurse can initiate without a physician order, within nursing scope of practice. Examples: repositioning a patient every 2 hours, teaching deep breathing exercises, applying compression stockings.</li>
          <li><strong>Dependent interventions</strong>: Actions that require a physician order. Examples: administering prescribed medications, performing ordered wound care, obtaining diagnostic labs.</li>
          <li><strong>Collaborative (interdependent) interventions</strong>: Actions planned and performed with other healthcare team members. Examples: physical therapy referral, dietitian consultation, respiratory therapy treatments.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Callout -->
        <div style="background:#eff6ff; border-left:4px solid #bfdbfe; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem 1.25rem; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; font-weight:700; color:#1d4ed8; margin-bottom:0.4rem;">📋 Clinical Example – Implementation</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; color:#1e3a5f; line-height:1.7; margin:0;">
            For a patient with impaired skin integrity (pressure ulcer Stage II on sacrum): The nurse
            performs an <strong>independent</strong> intervention by repositioning the patient off the sacrum
            every 2 hours and placing a foam wedge. She carries out a <strong>dependent</strong> intervention
            by applying the prescribed hydrocolloid dressing. She coordinates a <strong>collaborative</strong>
            intervention by referral to the wound care specialist and dietitian for nutritional optimisation.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Evaluation -->
        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Evaluation</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Evaluation is the final—yet ongoing—step. The nurse determines whether the patient has achieved
          the expected outcomes set during planning. It involves comparing the patient's actual response to
          the stated goals and deciding whether to continue, modify, or terminate the care plan.
        </p>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:0.75rem;"><strong>Three possible conclusions after evaluation:</strong></p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Goal met</strong>: Patient achieved the expected outcome → continue current plan or discharge/discontinue the nursing diagnosis.</li>
          <li><strong>Goal partially met</strong>: Patient progressed toward the goal but has not fully achieved it → modify the plan (adjust the goal, add interventions, revise the timeline).</li>
          <li><strong>Goal not met</strong>: Patient has made no progress or has deteriorated → reassess thoroughly; identify barriers; revise diagnosis, goals, or interventions entirely.</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Evaluation loops back to assessment—nursing is cyclical, not linear. If the goal is not met, the
          nurse must reassess to determine why: Was the assessment incomplete? Was the diagnosis incorrect?
          Were the interventions evidence-based and realistic? Was the goal SMART and patient-centred?
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- SECTION 2: Critical Thinking -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section id="critical-thinking" style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">
          2. Critical Thinking in Nursing
        </h2>

        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <strong>Critical thinking</strong> in nursing is a purposeful, disciplined, self-regulatory process
          of reasoning that nurses use to make sound clinical judgments. It is not simply memorising facts;
          it is the active, skillful application of knowledge to evaluate evidence, identify problems,
          consider alternatives, and determine the safest, most effective course of action for each patient.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Why Critical Thinking Is Essential in Nursing</h3>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li>Patients present with complex, multisystem problems that rarely match textbook cases exactly.</li>
          <li>Healthcare environments are dynamic—patient status changes rapidly, requiring constant reassessment.</li>
          <li>Nurses must prioritise care among multiple patients simultaneously, often with limited resources.</li>
          <li>Errors in nursing judgment can directly harm or kill patients; critical thinking reduces preventable errors.</li>
          <li>Evidence-based practice requires evaluating research and applying it appropriately to individual patients.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Clinical Judgment</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <strong>Clinical judgment</strong> is the outcome of critical thinking applied in a clinical context.
          It involves <em>noticing</em> relevant cues, <em>interpreting</em> their significance,
          <em>responding</em> with appropriate action, and <em>reflecting</em> on outcomes (Tanner's Clinical
          Judgment Model, 2006). The NCSBN's Next Generation NCLEX (NGN) Clinical Judgment Measurement Model
          describes six cognitive skills nurses must demonstrate: recognise cues, analyse cues, prioritise
          hypotheses, generate solutions, take action, and evaluate outcomes.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Critical Thinking at Each ADPIE Step</h3>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Assessment</strong>: Deciding what data to collect, which sources are most reliable, what is clinically significant, and what should be validated further.</li>
          <li><strong>Diagnosis</strong>: Clustering data, recognising patterns, differentiating actual vs. risk vs. wellness diagnoses, avoiding premature closure (settling on an incorrect diagnosis too quickly).</li>
          <li><strong>Planning</strong>: Setting realistic, patient-centred goals; selecting interventions based on evidence; anticipating complications.</li>
          <li><strong>Implementation</strong>: Adapting interventions to the patient's current response; recognising when a planned action is no longer safe or appropriate.</li>
          <li><strong>Evaluation</strong>: Objectively determining whether goals were met; willingness to revise the plan when outcomes are not achieved.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Attributes of a Critical Thinker in Nursing</h3>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Inquisitiveness</strong>: Asks "why?" and seeks to understand the underlying pathophysiology, not just the protocol.</li>
          <li><strong>Open-mindedness</strong>: Considers alternative diagnoses and interventions; does not dismiss patient or family input.</li>
          <li><strong>Analytical thinking</strong>: Breaks complex situations into components; examines cause-and-effect relationships.</li>
          <li><strong>Self-confidence</strong>: Trusts clinical judgment and is willing to advocate for the patient, even when this requires questioning orders.</li>
          <li><strong>Contextual perspective</strong>: Considers the patient as a whole person, including cultural, psychosocial, and environmental factors.</li>
          <li><strong>Intellectual integrity</strong>: Applies the same standards of reasoning regardless of personal bias or convenience.</li>
          <li><strong>Creativity</strong>: Generates novel, individualised solutions when standard approaches are inadequate.</li>
          <li><strong>Reflection</strong>: Evaluates own reasoning and practice to identify areas for improvement.</li>
        </ul>

        <div style="background:#eff6ff; border-left:4px solid #bfdbfe; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem 1.25rem; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; font-weight:700; color:#1d4ed8; margin-bottom:0.4rem;">📋 Clinical Example – Critical Thinking</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; color:#1e3a5f; line-height:1.7; margin:0;">
            A nurse assesses a post-operative patient and notices mild confusion and a drop in urine output
            from 60 mL/hr to 15 mL/hr over two hours. A novice nurse might chart the observation and wait
            for rounds. A <strong>critically thinking nurse</strong> recognises these as early signs of
            hypovolaemia or haemorrhage, checks the surgical drain output, auscultates lung sounds, re-checks
            BP (now 94/60 mmHg from 120/78 mmHg earlier), and immediately notifies the surgeon using SBAR—
            potentially preventing haemorrhagic shock.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- SECTION 3: Assessment Interview Techniques -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section id="interview-techniques" style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">
          3. Assessment Interview Techniques
        </h2>

        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          The <strong>assessment interview</strong> is the structured conversation between nurse and patient
          that forms the foundation of subjective data collection. Expert interview technique maximises
          the quality and completeness of the data obtained, builds trust, and establishes the therapeutic
          relationship that underpins all subsequent nursing care.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Open-Ended vs. Closed Questions</h3>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Open-ended questions</strong> invite the patient to elaborate and share their perspective freely. They cannot be answered with a single word. Example: <em>"Can you describe what your pain feels like?"</em> or <em>"Tell me what has been worrying you most."</em> Use early in the interview to gather broad information.</li>
          <li><strong>Closed questions</strong> elicit specific, focused information and can be answered "yes/no" or with a number. Example: <em>"Is the pain sharp or dull?"</em> or <em>"On a scale of 0–10, how would you rate your pain?"</em> Use to clarify or obtain precise data.</li>
          <li><strong>Leading questions</strong> should be <em>avoided</em> as they suggest the "correct" answer and bias the response. Example (problematic): <em>"You're not having chest pain, are you?"</em></li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Active Listening</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Active listening is a deliberate process of receiving, processing, and responding to the patient's
          verbal and nonverbal communication. It includes: making and maintaining appropriate eye contact;
          leaning slightly forward; nodding affirmatively; avoiding interruptions; allowing the patient to
          complete sentences; and reflecting back what you have heard (<em>"So it sounds like the pain started
          after you lifted the box—is that right?"</em>). Active listening signals respect and
          interest and dramatically increases the patient's willingness to share sensitive information.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Clarification</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          When a patient's statement is vague or ambiguous, the nurse asks for clarification to ensure
          accurate data. Clarification prevents incorrect assumptions. Example: Patient says, <em>"I feel
          awful."</em> The nurse responds: <em>"When you say you feel awful, can you describe specifically
          what you're experiencing?"</em> Clarification avoids interpreting the patient's experience through
          the nurse's own framework.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Reflection</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Reflection involves repeating the patient's own words or paraphrasing their statements to
          encourage further exploration and to demonstrate understanding. Example: Patient states, <em>"I'm
          worried about my surgery tomorrow."</em> Nurse reflects: <em>"You're worried about your surgery."</em>
          This technique validates the patient's feelings and invites elaboration without redirecting the
          conversation.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Silence as a Technique</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Therapeutic silence is a deliberate, purposeful pause that gives the patient time to think,
          feel, and formulate a response without pressure. Many nurses fill silences out of discomfort,
          inadvertently cutting off important disclosures. Silence communicates patience, respect, and
          genuine interest. It is particularly valuable when a patient is emotional, grieving, or processing
          difficult information. The nurse remains present and attentive during silence—not distracted by
          a computer or chart.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Body Language and Nonverbal Communication</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Research suggests that the majority of communication is nonverbal. During the assessment interview,
          the nurse should attend to both her own and the patient's nonverbal cues:
        </p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Nurse's posture</strong>: Sit at eye level rather than standing over the patient; avoid crossing arms (signals defensiveness); face the patient directly.</li>
          <li><strong>Proximity</strong>: Respect personal and cultural space preferences; generally 1–1.5 meters is appropriate.</li>
          <li><strong>Facial expression</strong>: Remain open and non-judgmental; avoid expressions of shock, disgust, or disbelief.</li>
          <li><strong>Patient cues</strong>: Note incongruence between verbal and nonverbal communication (e.g., patient says "I'm fine" while wincing and guarding abdomen). Document and explore discrepancies.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">Therapeutic Communication During Assessment</h3>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li><strong>Introduce yourself</strong> and explain the purpose of the interview to put the patient at ease.</li>
          <li><strong>Ensure privacy</strong>: Close the curtain or door; if a family member is present, confirm with the patient that they are comfortable proceeding.</li>
          <li><strong>Use plain language</strong>: Avoid medical jargon; adjust vocabulary to the patient's health literacy level.</li>
          <li><strong>Non-judgmental approach</strong>: Respond to disclosures (e.g., substance use, sexual history, mental health history) without visible judgement. Example: Instead of "That was a bad idea," respond "Thank you for telling me that—it's important for your care."</li>
          <li><strong>Empathy</strong>: Acknowledge and validate the patient's emotions before redirecting to clinical questions. <em>"That sounds really frightening. I want to make sure we understand exactly what's been happening for you."</em></li>
          <li><strong>Summarise</strong>: At the end of the interview, briefly summarise the key information gathered and give the patient an opportunity to correct or add to it.</li>
        </ul>

        <div style="background:#eff6ff; border-left:4px solid #bfdbfe; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem 1.25rem; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; font-weight:700; color:#1d4ed8; margin-bottom:0.4rem;">📋 Clinical Example – Interview Technique</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; color:#1e3a5f; line-height:1.7; margin:0;">
            A nurse is admitting a 45-year-old man with chest pain. She sits at his bedside (eye level),
            introduces herself, closes the curtain, and begins with an <strong>open-ended question</strong>:
            <em>"Mr. J., can you describe in your own words what brought you in today?"</em> He begins
            speaking, and she actively listens without interrupting. When he says, "It gets really bad
            sometimes," she uses <strong>clarification</strong>: <em>"When you say really bad—can you tell
            me what that means? How would you rate it on a scale of 0–10?"</em> She uses
            <strong>silence</strong> after he pauses to recall timing details, allowing him to
            complete his thought uninterrupted.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- SECTION 4: Steps Overview -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section id="steps-overview" style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">
          4. Steps of the Nursing Process
        </h2>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          The following numbered format is designed for clinical recall and exam preparation. The nursing
          process is <strong>cyclic and continuous</strong>—it does not end after evaluation but loops back
          to assessment as patient status changes.
        </p>

        <ol style="line-height:1.9; color:#374151; padding-left:1.5rem; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.85rem;">
            <strong>Assessment (A)</strong><br />
            Collect subjective data (interview) and objective data (physical exam, records, labs).
            Use a systematic, head-to-toe or body-systems approach. Validate data. Document findings.
            <em>Key question: What is the patient experiencing?</em>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.85rem;">
            <strong>Diagnosis (D)</strong><br />
            Analyse and cluster data to identify patterns. Formulate NANDA-I nursing diagnoses in
            PES format (actual) or "Risk for…" format (risk). Prioritise diagnoses using Maslow's hierarchy
            and ABC (Airway &gt; Breathing &gt; Circulation). Distinguish nursing diagnoses from
            medical diagnoses.
            <em>Key question: What nursing problems does the data indicate?</em>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.85rem;">
            <strong>Planning (P)</strong><br />
            Write SMART, patient-centred expected outcomes. Select evidence-based nursing interventions.
            Involve the patient and family in care planning. Document the care plan.
            <em>Key question: What outcomes do we want, and how will we achieve them?</em>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.85rem;">
            <strong>Implementation (I)</strong><br />
            Reassess before acting. Carry out independent, dependent, and collaborative interventions.
            Provide patient education. Document interventions immediately after completion with time,
            date, and nurse's signature.
            <em>Key question: What actions will be taken?</em>
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom:0.85rem;">
            <strong>Evaluation (E)</strong><br />
            Compare actual patient outcomes to expected outcomes. Determine if goals were met,
            partially met, or not met. Revise the care plan as needed. Loop back to reassessment.
            <em>Key question: Did the patient achieve the expected outcomes?</em>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <!-- Summary table -->
        <div style="overflow-x:auto; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          <table style="width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:0.875rem; color:#374151;">
            <thead>
              <tr style="background:#eef2ff; border-bottom:2px solid #c7d2fe;">
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:0.6rem 0.8rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b;">Step</th>
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:0.6rem 0.8rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b;">Verb</th>
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:0.6rem 0.8rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b;">Key Output</th>
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:0.6rem 0.8rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b;">Who leads?</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              {[
                ['Assessment', 'Collect & Validate', 'Patient database (subjective + objective)', 'Nurse'],
                ['Diagnosis', 'Analyse & Interpret', 'Prioritised nursing diagnosis list', 'Nurse'],
                ['Planning', 'Set Goals & Select Interventions', 'Individualised care plan', 'Nurse + Patient'],
                ['Implementation', 'Act', 'Interventions performed; patient education delivered', 'Nurse + Team'],
                ['Evaluation', 'Measure & Revise', 'Goal-met determination; revised plan', 'Nurse'],
              ].map(([step, verb, output, who]) => (
                <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
                  <td style="padding:0.6rem 0.8rem; font-weight:600; color:#6366f1;">{step}</td>
                  <td style="padding:0.6rem 0.8rem;">{verb}</td>
                  <td style="padding:0.6rem 0.8rem;">{output}</td>
                  <td style="padding:0.6rem 0.8rem;">{who}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- SECTION 5: Most Important Thing During Assessment -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section id="assessment-importance" style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size:1.15rem; font-weight:700; color:#1e293b; margin-bottom:0.75rem; padding-bottom:0.5rem; border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;">
          5. Most Important Thing During Assessment
        </h2>

        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          If you remember only one thing about assessment, remember this: the most important purpose of
          the assessment phase is to <strong>collect complete and accurate data</strong>. Every subsequent
          step—diagnosis, planning, implementation, and evaluation—depends entirely on the quality of data
          collected in this phase. An inaccurate or incomplete assessment will produce an incorrect diagnosis,
          an inappropriate plan, ineffective interventions, and meaningless evaluation.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">1. Collecting Complete and Accurate Data</h3>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li>Gather data from <strong>multiple sources</strong>: patient, family, records, team members, diagnostics.</li>
          <li>Use a <strong>structured, systematic framework</strong> (head-to-toe or body systems) to ensure all areas are assessed.</li>
          <li><strong>Validate</strong> data that seems unexpected or inconsistent—repeat measurements, cross-check with other sources.</li>
          <li>Document <strong>immediately and accurately</strong>; delayed documentation relies on memory and introduces error.</li>
          <li>Collect <strong>both subjective AND objective data</strong>—neither alone gives a complete picture. Subjective data tells you what the patient experiences; objective data provides measurable evidence. Together they are the basis of the nursing diagnosis.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">2. The Therapeutic Relationship</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          A <strong>therapeutic nurse-patient relationship</strong> is the essential foundation for
          effective assessment. Patients who trust their nurse disclose more complete and accurate
          information, including sensitive details about substance use, mental health, sexual history,
          or non-adherence to treatment. Building this relationship begins the moment the nurse enters
          the room: introduce yourself by name and role, maintain eye contact, sit at the patient's
          level, and demonstrate genuine interest and empathy.
        </p>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">3. Non-Judgmental Approach</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          A non-judgmental approach means the nurse acknowledges and accepts the patient's values,
          beliefs, behaviours, and disclosures <strong>without expressing criticism or disapproval</strong>,
          even when those behaviours conflict with the nurse's own values or recommended health practices.
          Judgmental responses cause patients to withhold critical information, compromising the accuracy
          of the database. A non-judgmental posture includes:
        </p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li>Neutral, factual language: <em>"How many alcoholic drinks do you have per day?"</em> rather than <em>"You don't drink too much, do you?"</em></li>
          <li>Controlled facial expression and body language when hearing unexpected disclosures.</li>
          <li>Explicitly thanking the patient for sharing sensitive information: <em>"Thank you for telling me—this helps me give you better care."</em></li>
          <li>Separating personal values from professional responsibilities.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="font-size:1rem; font-weight:700; color:#6366f1; margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;">4. Subjective AND Objective Data—Both Are Required</h3>
        <p style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem;">
          Nurses sometimes undervalue subjective data because it "can't be measured," or overlook subtle
          objective findings because the patient "looks fine." <strong>Both types of data are equally essential</strong>.
        </p>
        <ul style="line-height:1.8; color:#374151; margin-bottom:1rem; padding-left:1.5rem;">
          <li>Subjective data captures the patient's experience—their pain, fear, nausea, fatigue, and goals. It cannot be inferred from objective findings alone.</li>
          <li>Objective data provides measurable evidence that validates, contradicts, or adds context to what the patient reports.</li>
          <li>When subjective and objective data conflict, the nurse must investigate further rather than dismissing one in favour of the other.</li>
        </ul>

        <div style="background:#eff6ff; border-left:4px solid #bfdbfe; border-radius:0.5rem; padding:1rem 1.25rem; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; font-weight:700; color:#1d4ed8; margin-bottom:0.4rem;">📋 Clinical Example – Importance of Assessment Quality</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem; color:#1e3a5f; line-height:1.7; margin:0;">
            A 55-year-old woman is admitted with "abdominal discomfort." She mentions to her nurse,
            almost as an afterthought, <em>"I also feel pressure in my jaw and my left arm feels
            heavy."</em> A nurse focused only on the chief complaint (abdominal pain) and objective
            abdominal findings might miss this critical subjective disclosure. A thorough assessment—
            including comprehensive review of all symptoms in the patient's own words—immediately
            raises concern for an <strong>atypical MI presentation</strong> (more common in women).
            The nurse orders a STAT 12-lead ECG and notifies the physician. This is the power of
            complete assessment.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

